<MainLayout title="Five grid connection risks to address early | IKAI Insights" description="Five grid connection risks to address early">
  <section class="page-hero"><div class="container"><span class="eyebrow light">IKAI Insight</span><h1>Five grid connection risks to address early</h1><p class="lead">Practical perspectives from IKAI Energy Consulting.</p></div></section>
  <section class="section"><article class="container prose">
    <p>Grid connection risk is rarely limited to one study or one technical issue. It usually develops across modelling, performance requirements, stakeholder expectations and project design.</p><h2>1. An unclear connection strategy</h2><p>Before detailed studies begin, the project team should understand the likely connection pathway, technical constraints, evidence requirements and decision points. Early alignment reduces rework.</p><h2>2. Model maturity does not match the project stage</h2><p>Models often evolve while plant design and control settings are still changing. A clear model governance process helps ensure studies use the right version and assumptions.</p><h2>3. Control interactions are identified too late</h2><p>For inverter-based resources, EMT analysis may reveal interactions that are not visible in RMS studies. Early screening can avoid late redesign.</p><h2>4. Stakeholder engagement is reactive</h2><p>AEMO and NSP questions are easier to resolve when the project maintains a consistent technical narrative, evidence trail and accountable action list.</p><h2>5. Connection assumptions are not linked to contracts</h2><p>Performance obligations, plant capability and contractor scope should align. Gaps between connection commitments and procurement specifications create delivery risk.</p><p>The practical lesson is simple: connection risk should be managed as an integrated project workstream, not as a standalone study package.</p>
    <hr/>
